# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: braid-breaker
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] In electrical engineering, **admittance** is a measure of how easily a circuit or device will allow a current to flow.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] It is defined as the reciprocal of impedance, analogous to how conductance and resistance are defined.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] The SI unit of admittance is the siemens (symbol S); the older, synonymous unit is mho, and its symbol is ℧ (an upside-down uppercase omega Ω).
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] Oliver Heaviside coined the term *admittance* in December 1887.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] Heaviside used Y to represent the magnitude of admittance, but it quickly became the conventional symbol for admittance itself through the publications of Charles Proteus Steinmetz.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] Heaviside probably chose Y simply because it is next to Z in the alphabet, the conventional symbol for impedance.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] Resistance is a measure of the opposition of a circuit to the flow of a steady current, while impedance takes into account not only the resistance but also dynamic effects (known as reactance).
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] The dynamic effects of the material's susceptance relate to the universal dielectric response, the power law scaling of a system's admittance with frequency under alternating current conditions.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] Note that (as shown above) the signs of reactances become reversed in the admittance domain; i.e. capacitive susceptance is positive and inductive susceptance is negative.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] In the context of electrical modeling of transformers and transmission lines, shunt components that provide paths of least resistance in certain models are generally specified in terms of their admittance.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] Each side of most transformer models contains shunt components which model magnetizing current and core losses.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] These shunt components can be referenced to the primary or secondary side.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] For simplified transformer analysis, admittance from shunt elements can be neglected.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] When shunt components have non-negligible effects on system operation, the shunt admittance must be considered.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] In the diagram below, all shunt admittances are referred to the primary side.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] The real and imaginary components of the shunt admittance, conductance and susceptance, are represented by *G*c and B, respectively.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] Transmission lines can span hundreds of kilometers, over which the line's capacitance can affect voltage levels.
[src:braid-breaker/admittance] For short length transmission line analysis, which applies to lines shorter than 80 kilometres (50 mi), this capacitance can be ignored and shunt components are not necessary in the model.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The amateur radio service (*amateur service* and *amateur-satellite service*) is established by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) through its Radio Regulations.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] National governments set technical and operational rules for transmissions and issue individual station licences with unique call signs.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Call signs must be used in transmissions, at least every ten minutes and at the end of the conversation.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Amateur radio operators must hold an amateur radio licence, granted after an examination that tests knowledge of radio theory, electronics, and national regulations.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Operators are authorised to transmit on frequency ranges allocated internationally as the *amateur radio bands*.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Within these bands they may use any frequency, though some are restricted to particular modes of voice, text, image, or data communications.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] This allows communication locally, nationally, worldwide, and even with stations in space.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In many countries, operators may also exchange radio communications between computers or transceivers connected through virtual private networks on the Internet.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Amateur radio is represented by the International Amateur Radio Union (IARU), which has three regions and includes national amateur radio societies in most countries.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In 2011 the American Radio Relay League (the U.S. national society) estimated that about 2 million people worldwide were active in amateur radio.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] About 830,000 amateur radio stations are in Region 2 (the Americas), about 750,000 in Region 3 (South and East Asia and the Pacific), and about 400,000 in Region 1 (Europe, the Middle East, the CIS and Africa).
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Radio amateurs have been credited with a number of advancements, notably the discovery of skywave propagation.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The origins of amateur radio can be traced to the late 19th century, but amateur radio as practised today began in the early 20th century.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The *First Annual Official Wireless Blue Book of the Wireless Association of America*, produced in 1909, contains a list of amateur radio stations.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] This radio callbook lists wireless telegraph stations in Canada and the United States, including 89 amateur radio stations.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] As with radio in general, amateur radio was associated with various amateur experimenters and hobbyists.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Amateur radio enthusiasts have significantly contributed to science, engineering, industry, and social services.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Research by amateur operators has founded new industries, like experimentation with quartz piezoelectric resonators from 1924 until about 1934, built economies, empowered nations, and saved lives in times of emergency.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Ham radio can also be used in the classroom to teach English, map skills, geography, math, science, and computer skills.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The term *ham* was originally a pejorative, used in professional wired telegraphy during the 19th century to mock operators with poor Morse code-sending skills ("ham-fisted").
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] This term continued to be used after the invention of radio and the subsequent proliferation of amateur experimentation with wireless telegraphy; among both land-based and sea-based professional radio telegraphers, *ham* amateurs were considered a nuisance.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The use of *ham* to mean amateurish or unskilled survives to this day in another discipline— i.e.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The amateur radio community subsequently reclaimed the word as a label of pride, and by the mid-20th century it had lost its pejorative meaning.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Although not an acronym or initialism, it is occasionally written as "HAM" in capital letters.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Amateur radio combines communication, technical experimentation, and recreation.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Operators take part in contests, provide emergency service, build and modify equipment, and use transmission modes ranging from traditional Morse code to modern digital protocols.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Operators often join conversational groups and take part in scheduled on-air meetings called nets, coordinated by a net control station.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Nets may provide training for emergencies, operate as informal discussions, or focus on specialised topics.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] With battery- or generator-powered equipment, operators frequently provide communication during natural disasters when commercial services are unavailable.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Competitive activities include contests to contact as many stations as possible in a set period, and operating awards such as Summits on the Air, Worked All States, and Jamboree on the Air.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Operators also contribute to citizen science by collecting propagation data and supporting atmospheric science research.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The principal voice modes are frequency modulation (FM), single sideband (SSB), and amplitude modulation (AM).
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] FM offers high audio quality, SSB is efficient for long-distance use, and AM continues among users of vintage amateur radio equipment.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Radiotelegraphy using International Morse code, or Continuous Wave (CW), is one of the oldest modes in amateur radio.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Although largely replaced in professional services, it remains in use on shortwave bands because it functions under weak-signal conditions and employs internationally understood codes such as the Q code.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] CW is also used by hobbyists who build their own equipment (home construction) and by operators engaged in low-power operation, as CW transmitters are simple to construct and weak signals can often be received by ear.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Until 2003, Morse code proficiency was required under international regulations for access to frequencies below 30 MHz.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The requirement was withdrawn in the United States in 2007.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Personal computers have enabled new digital transmission modes.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Radioteletype (RTTY), once operated by mechanical devices, is now handled in software.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Packet radio, developed in the 1970s, uses protocols such as AX.25 and TCP/IP.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Later modes including PSK31 and FT8 allow efficient low-signal communication on shortwave bands.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Radio over IP (RoIP) applies Internet-based telephony techniques to radio.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] EchoLink and the Internet Radio Linking Project link repeaters and operators worldwide.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Other specialised modes support weak-signal communication.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Automatic link establishment (ALE) maintains networks on high-frequency bands, while the WSJT suite supports meteor scatter and moonbounce.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Fast-scan amateur television (ATV) adapts consumer video equipment to transmit images.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] It typically operates on the 70 cm (420–450 MHz) but may also use the 33 cm and higher frequencies.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Because of wide bandwidth requirements, ATV usually covers 30–100 km (20–60 mi).
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Linked repeater systems extend this range to several hundred kilometres.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Repeaters are often located on high ground or towers and may be linked by other amateur bands, landlines, or the Internet.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Operators can use amateur radio satellites, sometimes with only a hand-held transceiver.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Natural reflectors such as the Moon, the aurora borealis, and meteor trails are also used.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Licensed astronauts have also made contacts from the International Space Station through the ARISS programme.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Because radio signals can propagate across national borders, amateur radio is regulated by governments under international frameworks.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] National requirements generally follow standards set by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) and World Radiocommunication Conferences.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Most countries require candidates to pass an examination that tests electronics, radio propagation, operating practices, and regulations.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Licensing grants access to a broader portion of the spectrum, additional communication modes, and higher transmitter power than unlicensed personal radio services such as CB, FRS, or PMR446.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Examination systems often include several levels, each granting wider frequency access and higher power limits.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In the United Kingdom and Australia, entry-level candidates must also complete a practical skills test to obtain the Foundation Licence, the first of three licensing stages.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Each licensee is normally assigned a unique call sign.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Some countries issue additional station licences, or recognise club and organisational licences.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Licences are generally valid only in the issuing country or in states with reciprocal agreements.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In some jurisdictions, a licence is also required to purchase or possess amateur radio equipment.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In the United States, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) issues three licence classes: Technician, General, and Amateur Extra.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Examinations are administered by accredited Volunteer Examiners through the FCC's Volunteer Examiner Coordinator system.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Higher licence classes provide access to more frequency bands and higher transmitter power.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The tests cover regulations, operating practices, electronics theory, equipment design, and safety.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Licences are valid for ten years, and the national question pools are published in advance and updated every four years.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Prospective amateur radio operators are examined on understanding of the key concepts of electronics, radio equipment, antennas, radio propagation, RF safety, and the radio regulations of the government granting the license.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] These examinations are sets of questions typically posed in either a short answer or multiple-choice format.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Examinations can be administered by bureaucrats, non-paid certified examiners, or previously licensed amateur radio operators.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The ease with which an individual can acquire an amateur radio license varies from country to country.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In some countries, examinations may be offered only once or twice a year in the national capital and can be inordinately bureaucratic (for example in India) or challenging because some amateurs must undergo difficult security approval (as in Iran).
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Currently, only Yemen and North Korea do not issue amateur radio licenses to their citizens.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Some developing countries, especially those in Africa, Asia, and Latin America, require the payment of annual license fees that can be prohibitively expensive for most of their citizens.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] A few small countries may not have a national licensing process and may instead require prospective amateur radio operators to take the licensing examinations of a foreign country.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In countries with the largest numbers of amateur radio licensees, such as Japan, the United States, Thailand, Canada, and most of the countries in Europe, there are frequent license examinations opportunities in major cities.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Granting a separate license to a club or organization generally requires that an individual with a current and valid amateur radio license who is in good standing with the telecommunications authority assumes responsibility for any operations conducted under the club license or club call sign.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] A few countries may issue special licenses to novices or beginners that do not assign the individual a call sign but instead require the newly licensed individual to operate from stations licensed to a club or organization for a period of time before a higher class of license can be acquired.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] A reciprocal licensing agreement between two countries allows licensed amateur radio operators from one country to operate stations in the other without obtaining a new licence.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In some cases, visiting operators may be issued a temporary local licence and call sign.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Some countries have bilateral or multilateral agreements that harmonise conditions, while others have no reciprocal arrangements.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Regional organisations, such as the Organization of American States, facilitate reciprocity through treaties, including the Inter-American Amateur Radio Service Convention.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Many people start their involvement in amateur radio on social media or by finding a local club.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Clubs often provide information about licensing, local operating practices, and technical advice.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Newcomers also often study independently by purchasing books or other materials, sometimes with the help of a mentor, teacher, or friend.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In North America, established amateurs who help newcomers are often referred to as "Elmers", as coined by Rodney Newkirk (W9BRD), within the ham community.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In addition, many countries have national amateur radio societies which encourage newcomers and work with government communications regulation authorities for the benefit of all radio amateurs.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] An amateur radio operator uses a **call sign** on the air to legally identify the operator or station.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In some countries, the call sign assigned to the station must always be used, whereas in other countries, the call sign of either the operator or the station may be used.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In certain jurisdictions, an operator may also select a *"vanity"* call sign although these must also conform to the issuing government's allocation and structure used for amateur radio call signs.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Some jurisdictions require a fee to obtain a vanity call sign; in others, such as the UK, a fee is not required and the vanity call sign may be selected when the license is applied for.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The FCC in the U.S. discontinued its fee for vanity call sign applications in September 2015, but reinstated it at $35 in 2022.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The combination of the three parts identifies the specific transmitting station, and the station's identification (its call sign) is determined by the license held by its operator.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In the case of commercial stations and amateur club stations, the operator is a corporation; in the case of amateur radio operators, the license-holder is a resident of the country identified by the first part of the call sign.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Many countries do not follow the ITU convention for the second-part digit.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In the United Kingdom the original calls **G0**xxx, **G2**xxx, **G3**xxx, **G4**xxx, were Full (A) License holders along with the last **M0**xxx full call signs issued by the City & Guilds examination authority in December 2003.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Additional Full Licenses were originally granted to (B) Licenses with **G1**xxx, **G6**xxx, **G7**xxx, **G8**xxx and 1991 onward with **M1**xxx call signs.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The newer three-level Intermediate License holders are assigned **2E0**xxx and **2E1**xxx, and the basic Foundation License holders are granted call signs **M3**xxx, **M6**xxx or **M7**xxx.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Instead of using numbers, in the U.K. the second letter after the initial 'G' or 'M' identifies the station's location; for example, a call sign **G7OOE** becomes **GM7OOE** and **M0RDM** becomes **MM0RDM** when the license holder is operating their station in Scotland.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Intermediate licence call signs are slightly different.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] They begin **2**z**0** and **2**z**1** where the z is replaced with one of the country letters, as above.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The exception however is for England, whose letter would be 'E'; however, letter 'E' *is* used, but *only* in intermediate-level call signs, and perplexingly never by the advanced licenses.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] For example **2E0** & **2E1** are used whereas the call signs beginning 'G' or 'M' for foundation and full licenses never use the 'E'.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In the United States, for non-vanity licenses, the numeral indicates the geographical district the holder resided in when the license was first issued.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Prior to 1978, US hams were required to obtain a new call sign if they moved out of their geographic district.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Call signs starting with 'V' end with a number after to indicate the political region; whereas the prefix **CY** indicates geographic islands.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] **CY** is for amateurs operating from Sable Island (**CY0**) or St.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Special permission is required to visit either of these: from Parks Canada for Sable and Coast Guard for St.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The last two or three letters of the call signs are typically the operator's choice (upon completing the licensing test, the ham writes three most-preferred options).
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Two-letter call sign suffixes require a ham to have already been licensed for 5 years.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Call signs in Canada can be requested with a fee.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Also, for smaller geopolitical entities, the digit at the second or third character might be part of the country identification.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] For example, **VP2**xxx is in the British West Indies, which is subdivided into **VP2E**xx Anguilla, **VP2M**xx Montserrat, and **VP2V**xx British Virgin Islands.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] **VP5**xxx is in the Turks and Caicos Islands, **VP6**xxx is on Pitcairn Island, **VP8**xxx is in the Falklands, and **VP9**xxx is in Bermuda.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Online callbooks or call sign databases can be browsed or searched to find out who holds a specific call sign.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] An example of an online callbook is QRZ.com.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Various partial lists of famous people who hold or held amateur radio call signs have been compiled and published.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Many jurisdictions (but not in the U.K. nor Europe) may issue specialty vehicle registration plates to licensed amateur radio operators.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The fees for application and renewal are usually less than the standard rate for specialty plates.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In most administrations, unlike other RF spectrum users, radio amateurs may build or modify transmitting equipment for their own use within the amateur spectrum without the need to obtain government certification of the equipment.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Radio amateurs have access to frequency allocations throughout the RF spectrum, usually allowing choice of an effective frequency for communications across a local, regional, or worldwide path.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The shortwave bands, or HF, are suitable for worldwide communication, and the VHF and UHF bands normally provide local or regional communication, while the microwave bands have enough space, or bandwidth, for amateur television transmissions and high-speed computer networks.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In most countries, an amateur radio license grants permission to the license holder to own, modify, and operate equipment that is not certified by a governmental regulatory agency.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] This encourages amateur radio operators to experiment with home-constructed or modified equipment.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The use of such equipment must still satisfy national and international standards on spurious emissions.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Amateur radio operators are encouraged both by regulations and tradition of respectful use of the spectrum to use as little power as possible to accomplish the communication.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] This is to minimise interference or electromagnetic compatibility (EMC) to any other device.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Although allowable power levels are moderate by commercial standards, they are sufficient to enable global communication.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Lower license classes usually have lower power limits; for example, the lowest license class in the UK (Foundation licence) has a limit of 25 W.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Power limits vary from country to country and between license classes within a country.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Output power limits may also depend on the mode of transmission.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In Australia, for example, 400 W may be used for SSB transmissions, but FM and other modes are limited to 120 W.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Certain countries permit amateur radio licence holders to hold a Notice of Variation that allows higher power to be used than normally allowed for certain specific purposes.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] E.g. in the UK some amateur radio licence holders are allowed to transmit using (33 dBw) 2.0 kW for experiments entailing using the moon as a passive radio reflector (known as Earth–Moon–Earth communication) (EME).
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The International Telecommunication Union (ITU) governs the allocation of communications frequencies worldwide, with participation by each nation's communications regulation authority.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] National communications regulators have some liberty to restrict access to these bandplan frequencies or to award additional allocations as long as radio services in other countries do not suffer interference.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In some countries, specific emission types are restricted to certain parts of the radio spectrum, and in most other countries, International Amateur Radio Union (IARU) member societies adopt voluntary plans to ensure the most effective use of spectrum.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In a few cases, a national telecommunication agency may also allow hams to use frequencies outside of the internationally allocated amateur radio bands.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In Trinidad and Tobago, hams are allowed to use a repeater which is located on 148.800 MHz.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] This repeater is used and maintained by the National Emergency Management Agency (NEMA), but may be used by radio amateurs in times of emergency or during normal times to test their capability and conduct emergency drills.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] This repeater can also be used by non-ham NEMA staff and REACT members.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In Australia and New Zealand, ham operators are authorized to use one of the UHF TV channels.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Similarly, amateurs in the United States may apply to be registered with the Military Auxiliary Radio System (MARS).
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Once approved and trained, these amateurs also operate on US government military frequencies to provide contingency communications and morale message traffic support to the military services.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Amateurs use a variety of voice, text, image, and data communication modes over radio.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Generally new modes can be tested in the amateur radio service, although national regulations may require disclosure of a new mode to permit radio licensing authorities to monitor the transmissions.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Encryption, for example, is not generally permitted in the amateur radio service except for the special purpose of satellite vehicle control uplinks.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The following is a partial list of the modes of communication used, where the mode includes both modulation types and operating protocols.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] In former times, most amateur digital modes were transmitted by inserting audio into the microphone input of a radio and using an analog scheme, such as amplitude modulation (AM), frequency modulation (FM), or single-sideband modulation (SSB).
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] Beginning in 2017, increased use of several digital modes, particularly FT8, became popular within the amateur radio community.
[src:braid-breaker/amateur-radio] The following "modes" use no one specific modulation scheme but rather are classified by the activity of the communication.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The AWG originated in the number of drawing operations used to produce a given gauge of wire.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Very fine wire (for example, 30 gauge) required more passes through the drawing dies than 0 gauge wire did.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Manufacturers of wire formerly had proprietary wire gauge systems; the development of standardized wire gauges rationalized selection of wire for a particular purpose.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] While the AWG is essentially identical to the Brown & Sharpe (B&S) sheet metal gauge, the B&S gauge was designed for use with sheet metals.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] These are functionally interchangeable, but the use of B&S in relation to wire gauges, rather than sheet metal gauges, is technically improper.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Increasing gauge numbers denote logarithmically decreasing wire diameters, which is similar to many other non-metric gauging systems such as British Standard Wire Gauge (SWG).
[src:braid-breaker/awg] However, AWG is dissimilar to IEC 60228, the metric wire-size standard used in most parts of the world, based directly on the wire cross-section area (in square millimetres, mm2).
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The AWG tables are for a single, solid and round conductor.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The AWG of a stranded wire is determined by the cross-sectional area of the equivalent solid conductor.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Because there are also small gaps between the strands, a stranded wire will always have a slightly larger overall diameter than a solid wire with the same AWG.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] By definition, 36 AWG is 0.005 inches in diameter, and 0000 AWG is 0.46 inches (11.68 mm) in diameter.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The ratio of these diameters is 1:92, and there are 40 gauge sizes from 36 to 0000, or 39 steps.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Because each successive gauge number increases cross sectional area by a constant multiple, diameters vary geometrically.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Any two successive gauges (e.g., *A* and *B*) have diameters whose ratio (dia.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Similarly for gauges *n* steps apart, the diameter ratio of the first to last gauges is about 1.1229*n*.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Where *n* is the AWG size for gauges from 36 to 0.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The standard ASTM B258-02 (2008), *Standard Specification for Standard Nominal Diameters and Cross-Sectional Areas of AWG Sizes of Solid Round Wires Used as Electrical Conductors*, defines the ratio between successive sizes to be the 39th root of 92, or approximately 1.1229.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] ASTM B258-02 also dictates that wire diameters should be tabulated with no more than 4 significant figures, with a resolution of no more than 0.0001 inches (0.1 mils) for wires thicker than 44 AWG, and 0.00001 inches (0.01 mils) for wires 45 AWG and thinner.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Sizes with multiple zeros are successively thicker than 0 AWG and can be denoted using "*number of zeros*/0", for example 4/0 AWG for 0000 AWG.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] For an m/0 AWG wire, use *n* = −(*m* − 1) = 1 − *m* in the above formulas.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The table below shows various data including both the resistance of the various wire gauges and the allowable current (ampacity) based on a copper conductor with plastic insulation.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The diameter information in the table applies to *solid* wires.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Stranded wires are calculated by calculating the equivalent cross sectional copper wire area.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Fusing current (melting wire) is estimated based on 25 °C (77 °F) ambient temperature.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The table below assumes DC, or AC frequencies equal to or less than 60 Hz, and does not take skin effect into account.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] "Turns of wire per unit length" refers to wire wound in a helix with the turns touching, as in a solenoid and is therefore the reciprocal of the conductor diameter.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] As wire in such a coil normally has insulation, this figure forms an upper bound.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] In the North American electrical industry, conductors thicker than 4/0 AWG are generally identified by the area in thousands of circular mils (kcmil), where 1 kcmil = 0.5067 mm2.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The next wire size thicker than 4/0 has a cross section of 250 kcmil.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] A *circular mil* is the area of a wire one mil in diameter.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] One million circular mils is the area of a circle with 1,000 mil (1 inch) diameter.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] An older abbreviation for one thousand circular mils is *MCM*.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] AWG can also be used to describe stranded wire.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The AWG size of a stranded wire represents the sum of the cross-sectional diameter of the individual strands; the gaps between strands are not counted.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] When made with circular strands, these gaps occupy about 25% of the wire area, thus requiring the overall bundle diameter to be about 13% larger than a solid wire of equal gauge.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Stranded wires are specified with three numbers, the overall AWG size, the number of strands, and the AWG size of a strand.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] The number of strands and the AWG size of a strand are separated by a slash.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] For example, a 22 AWG 7/30 stranded wire is a 22 AWG wire made from seven strands of 30 AWG wire.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] As indicated in the Formulae and Rules of thumb sections above, differences in AWG size translate directly into ratios of diameter or area.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] This property can be employed to easily find the AWG size of a stranded bundle by measuring the diameter and count of its strands.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] (This only applies to bundles with circular strands of identical size.) To find the AWG size of 7-strand wire with equal strands, subtract 8.4 from the AWG size of a strand.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Similarly, for 19-strand subtract 12.7, and for 37 subtract 15.6.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Measuring strand diameter is often easier and more accurate than attempting to measure bundle diameter and packing ratio.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Such measurement can be done with a wire gauge go-no-go tool or with a caliper or micrometer.
[src:braid-breaker/awg] Alternative ways are commonly used in the electrical industry to specify wire sizes as AWG.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] In telecommunications and professional audio, a **balanced line** or **balanced signal pair** is an electrical circuit consisting of two conductors of the same type, both of which have equal impedances along their lengths, to ground, and to other circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The primary advantage of the balanced line format is good rejection of common-mode noise and interference when fed to a differential device such as a transformer or differential amplifier.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The combination of a balanced line and differential signaling in audio applications is balanced audio and is commonly used in sound reinforcement and sound recording and reproduction.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Another common form of balanced line is twin-lead, used for radio frequency communications.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Also common is twisted pair, used for traditional telephone, professional audio, or for data communications.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] They are to be contrasted to unbalanced lines, such as coaxial cable, which is designed to have its return conductor connected to ground, or circuits whose return conductor actually is ground (see earth-return telegraph).
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Balanced and unbalanced circuits can be interfaced using a device called a balun.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Circuits driving balanced lines must themselves be balanced to maintain the benefits of balance.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This may be achieved by transformer coupling (repeating coils) or by merely balancing the impedance in each conductor.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Lines carrying symmetric signals (those with equal amplitudes but opposite polarities on each leg) are often incorrectly referred to as "balanced", but this is actually differential signalling.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Balanced lines and differential signalling are often used together, but they are not the same thing.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Differential signalling does not make a line balanced, nor does noise rejection in balanced cables require differential signalling.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Transmission of a signal over a balanced line reduces the influence of noise or interference due to external stray electric fields.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Any external signal sources tend to induce only a common-mode signal on the line, and the balanced impedances to ground minimizes differential pickup due to stray electric fields.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The conductors are sometimes twisted together to ensure that each conductor is equally exposed to any external magnetic fields that could induce unwanted noise.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Some balanced lines also have electrostatic shielding to reduce the amount of noise introduced.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The cable is often wrapped in foil, copper wire, or a copper braid.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This shield provides immunity to RF interference but does not provide immunity to magnetic fields.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Some balanced lines use 4-conductor star quad cable to provide immunity to magnetic fields.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The geometry of the cable ensures that magnetic fields will cause equal interference of both legs of the balanced circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This balanced interference is a common-mode signal that can easily be removed by a transformer or balanced differential receiver.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] A balanced line allows a differential receiver to reduce the noise on a connection by rejecting common-mode interference.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The lines have the same impedance to ground, so the interfering fields or currents induce the same voltage in both wires.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Since the receiver responds only to the difference between the wires, it is not influenced by the induced noise voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] If a balanced line is used in an unbalanced circuit, with different impedances from each conductor to ground, currents induced in the separate conductors will cause different voltage drops to ground, thus creating a voltage differential, making the line more susceptible to noise.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Examples of twisted pairs include category 5 cable.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Compared to unbalanced lines, balanced lines reduce the amount of noise per distance, allowing a longer cable run to be practical.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This is because electromagnetic interference will affect both signals the same way.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Similarities between the two signals are automatically removed at the end of the transmission path when one signal is subtracted from the other.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The first application for balanced lines was for telephone lines.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Interference that was of little consequence on a telegraph system (which is in essence digital) could be very disturbing for a telephone user.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The initial format was to take two single-wire unbalanced telegraph lines and use them as a pair.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This proved insufficient, however, with the growth of electric power transmission which tended to use the same routes.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] A telephone line running alongside a power line for many miles will inevitably have more interference induced in one leg than the other since one of them will be nearer to the power line.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This issue was addressed by swapping the positions of the two legs every few hundred yards with a cross-over, thus ensuring that both legs had equal interference induced and allowing common-mode rejection to do its work.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] As the telephone system grew, it became preferable to use cable rather than open wires to save space, and also to avoid poor performance during bad weather.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The cable construction used for balanced telephone cables was twisted pair; however, this did not become widespread until repeater amplifiers became available.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] For an unamplified telephone line, a twisted pair cable could only manage a maximum distance of 30 km.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Open wires, on the other hand, with their lower capacitance, had been used for enormous distances—the longest was the 1500 km from New York to Chicago built in 1893.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Loading coils were used to improve the distance achievable with cable but the problem was not finally overcome until amplifiers started to be installed in 1912.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Twisted pair balanced lines are still widely used for local loops, the lines that connect each subscriber's premises to their respective exchange.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Telephone trunk lines, and especially frequency division multiplexing carrier systems, are usually 4-wire circuits rather than 2-wire circuits (or at least they were before fibre-optic became widespread) and require a different kind of cable.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This format requires the conductors to be arranged in two pairs, one pair for the sending (go) signal and the other for the return signal.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The greatest source of interference on this kind of transmission is usually the crosstalk between the go and return circuits themselves.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The most common cable format is star quad, where the diagonally opposite conductors form the pairs.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This geometry gives maximum common-mode rejection between the two pairs.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] An alternative format is DM (Dieselhorst-Martin) quad which consists of two twisted pairs with the twisting at different pitches.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] An example of balanced lines is the connection of microphones to a mixer in professional systems.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Classically, both dynamic and condenser microphones used transformers to provide a differential-mode signal.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] While transformers are still used in the large majority of modern dynamic microphones, more recent condenser microphones are more likely to use electronic drive circuitry.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Each leg, irrespective of any signal, should have an identical impedance to ground.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Pair cable (or a pair-derivative such as star quad) is used to maintain the balanced impedances and close twisting of the cores ensures that any interference is common to both conductors.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Providing that the receiving end (usually a mixing console) does not disturb the line balance, and is able to ignore common-mode (noise) signals, and can extract differential ones, then the system will have excellent immunity to induced interference.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Typical professional audio sources, such as microphones, have three-pin XLR connectors.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] One connects to the shield or chassis ground, while the other two are for the signal conductors.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The signal wires can carry two copies of the same signal with opposite polarity (differential signalling) but need not do so.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] They are often termed "hot" and "cold," and the AES14-1992(r2004) Standard [and EIA Standard RS-297-A] suggest that the pin that carries the positive signal that results from a positive air pressure on a transducer will be deemed 'hot'.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Pin 2 has been designated as the 'hot' pin, and that designation serves useful for keeping a consistent polarity in the rest of the system.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Since these conductors travel the same path from source to destination, the assumption is that any interference is induced upon both conductors equally.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The appliance receiving the signals compares the difference between the two signals (often with disregard to electrical ground) allowing the appliance to ignore any induced electrical noise.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Any induced noise would be present in equal amounts and in identical polarity on each of the balanced signal conductors, so the two signals’ difference from each other would be unchanged.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The successful rejection of induced noise from the desired signal depends in part on the balanced signal conductors receiving the same amount and type of interference.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] This typically leads to twisted, braided, or co-jacketed cables for use in balanced signal transmission.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Many explanations of balanced lines assume symmetric signals (i.e. signals equal in magnitude but of opposite polarity) but this can lead to confusion of the two concepts—signal symmetry and balanced lines are quite independent of each other.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Essential in a balanced line is identical impedances in the two conductors in the driver, line and receiver (impedance balancing).
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] These conditions ensure that external noise affects each leg of the line equally and thus appears as a common-mode signal that is rejected by the receiver.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] There are balanced drive circuits that have excellent common-mode impedance balancing between the legs but do *not* provide symmetric signals.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Symmetric differential signals concern headroom and are not necessary for interference rejection.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Interfacing balanced and unbalanced lines requires a balun.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] For example, baluns can be used to send line level audio or E-carrier level 1 signals over coaxial cable (which is unbalanced) through 300 feet (91 m) of balanced category 5 cable by using a pair of baluns at each end of the CAT5 run.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] As the signal travels through the balanced line, noise is induced and added to the signal.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] As the CAT5 line is carefully impedance balanced, the noise induces equal (common-mode) voltages in both conductors.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] At the receiving end, the balun responds only to the difference in voltage between the two conductors, thus rejecting the noise picked up along the way and leaving the original signal intact.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] A once common application of a radio frequency balun was found at the antenna terminals of a television receiver.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Typically a 300-ohm balanced twin lead antenna input could only be connected to a coaxial cable from a cable TV system through a balun.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] The characteristic impedance $Z_{0}$ of a transmission line is an important parameter at higher frequencies of operation.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] where l is half the distance between the wire centres, R is the wire radius and $\mu$ , $\epsilon$ are respectively the permeability and permittivity of the surrounding medium.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] where $\epsilon _{r}$ is the relative permittivity of the surrounding medium.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] In electric power transmission, the three conductors used for three-phase power transmission are referred to as a balanced line since the instantaneous sum of the three line voltages is nominally zero.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] However, *balance* in this field is referring to the symmetry of the source and load: it has nothing to do with the impedance balance of the line itself, the sense of the meaning in telecommunications.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] For the transmission of single-phase electric power as used for railway electrification, two conductors are used to carry in-phase and out-of-phase voltages such that the line is balanced.
[src:braid-breaker/balanced-line] Bipolar HVDC lines at which each pole is operated with the same voltage toward ground are also balanced lines.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A **balun** /ˈbælʌn/ (from "balanced to unbalanced", originally, but now derived from "**balancing unit**") is an electrical device that allows balanced and unbalanced lines to be interfaced without disturbing the impedance arrangement of either line.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A balun can take many forms and may include devices that also transform impedances but need not do so.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Sometimes, in the case of transformer baluns, they use magnetic coupling but need not do so.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Common-mode chokes are also used as baluns and work by eliminating, rather than rejecting, common mode signals.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] In classical transformers, there are two electrically separate windings of wire coils around the transformer's core.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] This type is sometimes called a 'voltage balun'.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The primary winding receives the input signal, and the secondary winding puts out the converted signal.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The core that they are wound on may either be empty (air core) or, equivalently, a magnetically neutral material like a porcelain support, or it may be a material which is good magnetic conductor like ferrite in modern high-frequency (HF) baluns, or soft iron as in the early days of telegraphy.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The electrical signal in the primary coil is converted into a magnetic field in the transformer's core.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] When the electrical current through the primary reverses, it causes the established magnetic field to collapse.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The collapsing magnetic field then induces an electric field in the secondary winding.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The ratio of loops in each winding and the efficiency of the coils' magnetic coupling determines the ratio of electrical potential (voltage) to electrical current and the total power of the output.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] For idealized transformers, although the ratio of voltage to current will change in exact proportion to the square of the winding ratio, the power (measured in watts) remains identical.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] In real transformers, some energy is lost inside to heating of the metallic core of the transformer, to the AC and DC resistances of the winding conductors, and lost outside to the surrounding environment because of imperfect magnetic coupling between the two coils.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] An ideal balun consists of two wires (primary and secondary) and a core: the current in the primary wire generates a magnetic field in the core, which in turn induces an electric field in the secondary wire.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] An autotransformer balun has only one coil, or is made of two or more coils that have an electrical connection, wound around a core.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] One can also make an autotransformer from an ordinary transformer by cross-wiring the primary and secondary windings.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Baluns made with autotransformer windings are also called *voltage baluns*, since they produce balanced output voltage, but not necessarily balanced current.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] In all autotransformers, the single winding must have at least one extra electrical connection – called a *tap* or *tap point* – between the two ends of the winding.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The current sent into the balun through one pair of connections acts as if it were a primary coil, and magnetizes the entire core.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] When the electric current in the input segment of the coil changes, the induced magnetic field collapses and the collapse of the magnetic field in the core induces an electric current in the entire coil.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Electrical connections to parts of the coil different from the input connections have higher or lower voltages depending on the length of the coil that the output is tapped from.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Unlike transformer-type baluns, an autotransformer balun provides a path for DC current to ground from every terminal.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Since outdoor antennas are prone to build-up of static electric charge, the path for the static to drain to ground through an autotransformer balun can be a distinct advantage.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Transmission line or *choke* baluns can be considered as simple forms of transmission line transformers.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] This type is sometimes called a *current balun*, since it ensures equal current on both sides of its output, but not necessarily equal voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] These are normally called ununs, because they go from unbalanced to unbalanced or un-un.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Baluns are balanced to unbalanced or bal-un.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A more subtle type results when the transformer type (magnetic coupling) is combined with the transmission line type (electro-magnetic coupling).
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Most typically the same kind of transmission line wires are used for the windings as carry the signal from the radio to the antenna, although these baluns can be made using any type of wire.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The resulting devices have very wideband operation.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] *Transmission line transformers* commonly use small ferrite cores in toroidal rings or two-hole, binocular, shapes.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The Guanella transmission line transformer (Guanella 1944) is often combined with a balun to act as an impedance matching transformer.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Putting balancing aside a transformer of this type consists of a 75 Ω transmission line divided in parallel into two 150 Ω cables, which are then combined in series for 300 Ω.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] It is implemented as a specific wiring around the ferrite core of the balun.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Classic magnetic transformers are limited in maximum frequency due to the permeability of the magnetic material, which declines rapidly above MHz frequencies.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] This limits the operating frequency to around 1 GHz.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Microwave systems require baluns in the 1-100 GHz range for applications including mixers, push-pull amplifiers, and interface to differential analog to digital and digital to analog converters.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Transmission line transformer baluns with a high frequency transmission line such as a wirewound pair are able to operate at significantly higher frequencies (to 8 GHz and above) by combining capacitive coupling with magnetic coupling typical of classic magnetic transformers.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] To operate at even higher frequencies, magnetic loading becomes ineffective.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Nathan Marchand proposed a 'conversion transformer' that was capable of operation over a 1:3 bandwidth ratio in 1944.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] This basic circuit has been widely adapted and modified for use in planar structures (such as MMICs and RFICs) at frequencies up to at least 100 GHz.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] These types of planar baluns work exciting a mode in a ground plane or shield, which is then 'floated' away from the main ground.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] This allows extraction of the negative signal in addition to the main transmission line, creating positive and negative signal pairs.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] By connecting the positive and negative signal paths in various configurations dozens of balun configurations have been proposed and published in the electronics literature.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The electrical connection of capacitance and inductance leads to a frequency where the electrical reactance of the self-inductance and self-capacitance in the balun are equal in magnitude but opposite in sign: that is, to resonance.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A balun of any design operates poorly at or above its self-resonant frequency, and some of the design considerations for baluns are for the purpose of making the resonant frequency as far above the operating frequency as possible.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] An RF choke can be used in place of a balun.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] If a coil is made using coaxial cable near to the feed point of a balanced antenna, then the RF current that flows on the outer surface of the coaxial cable can be attenuated.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] One way of doing this would be to pass the cable through a ferrite toroid.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The end result is exactly the same as a 1:1 current balun (or Guanella-type balun).
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A balun's function is generally to achieve compatibility between systems, and as such, finds extensive application in modern communications, particularly in realising frequency conversion mixers to make cellular phone and data transmission networks possible.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] They are also used to send an E1 carrier signal from coaxial cable (BNC connector, 1.0/2.3 connector, 1.6/5.6 connector, Type 43 connectors) to UTP CAT-5 cable or IDC connector.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] In television, amateur radio, and other antenna installations and connections, baluns convert between impedances and symmetry of feedlines and antennas.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] For example, transformation of 300-Ω twin-lead or 450-Ω ladder line (balanced) to 75-Ω coaxial cable (unbalanced), or to directly connect a balanced antenna to unbalanced coaxial cable.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] To avoid feed line radiation, baluns are typically used as a form of common mode choke attached at the antenna feed point to prevent the coaxial cable from acting as an antenna and radiating power.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] This typically is needed when a balanced antenna (for instance, a dipole) is fed with coax; without a balun, the shield of the coax could couple with one side of the dipole, inducing common mode current, and becoming part of the antenna and unintentionally radiating.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] In measuring the impedance or radiation pattern of a balanced antenna using a coaxial cable, it is important to place a balun between the cable and the antenna feed.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Unbalanced currents that may otherwise flow on the cable will make the measured antenna impedance sensitive to the configuration of the feed cable, and the radiation pattern of small antennas may be distorted by radiation from the cable.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Baluns are present in radars, transmitters, satellites, in every telephone network, and probably in most wireless network modem/routers used in homes.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] It can be combined with transimpedance amplifiers to compose high-voltage amplifiers out of low-voltage components.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Baseband video uses frequencies up to several megahertz.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A balun can be used to couple video signals to twisted-pair cables instead of using coaxial cable.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Many security cameras now have both a balanced unshielded twisted pair (UTP) output and an unbalanced coaxial one via an internal balun.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A balun is also used on the video recorder end to convert back from the 100 Ω balanced to 75 Ω unbalanced.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A balun of this type has a BNC connector with two screw terminals.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] VGA/DVI baluns are baluns with electronic circuitry used to connect VGA/DVI sources (laptop, DVD, etc.) to VGA/DVI display devices over long runs of CAT-5/CAT-6 cable.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Runs over 130 m (400 ft) may lose quality because of attenuation and variations in the arrival time of each signal.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A skew control and special low skew or skew free cable is used for runs over 130 m (400 ft).
[src:braid-breaker/balun] In audio applications, baluns serve multiple purposes: they can convert between high-impedance unbalanced and low impedance balanced lines.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Another application is decoupling of devices (avoidance of earth loops).
[src:braid-breaker/balun] A third application of baluns in audio systems is in the provision of balanced mains power to the equipment.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] This noise infiltrates the audio/video system through the power supplies and raises the noise floor of the entire system.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] Except for the connections, the three devices in the image are electrically identical, but only the leftmost two can be used as baluns.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The device on the left would normally be used to connect a high impedance source, such as a guitar, into a balanced microphone input, serving as a passive DI unit.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The one in the center is for connecting a low impedance balanced source, such as a microphone, into a guitar amplifier.
[src:braid-breaker/balun] The one at the right is not a balun, as it provides only impedance matching.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] A **braid-breaker** is a filter that prevents television interference (TVI).
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] In many cases, TVI is caused by a high field strength of a nearby high frequency (HF) transmitter, the aerial down lead plugged into the back of the TV acts as a longwire antenna or as a simple vertical element.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The radio frequency (RF) current flowing through the tuner of the TV tends to generate harmonics which then spoil the viewing.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The braid breaker works by preventing RF signals picked up on the outside flowing into the TV set, while passing RF inside the coax from the antenna.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] Designs for diminishing unwanted signals are based on two types of filters: a “choke” filter which blocks signals in the electrical *mode* most interference uses, and filters that selectively admit or impede signals depending on the signal frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] Further, carefully chosen combinations of filters of either one type or both types multiply each other's effects, so that even if only slightly different, two filters are more effective than a single filter, or either filter alone.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] Ferrite ring chokes work by presenting a high impedance to signals traveling along the braid only, but passes through differential-mode ("balanced") currents unchanged.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The wanted signal is in differential mode with an equal and opposite current flowing in the braid to that in the cable core.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The alternating current in the braid is impeded by the magnetic fields created in the ferrite, effectively placing a large inductance in series with the braid.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The currents from the wanted signal, however, produce equal and opposite magnetic flux in the ferrite which cancel out.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The device is called a "choke" because the ferrite in effect "chokes off" the signal path for interference.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The other type of filters used are based on frequency: Below their operating frequency limit, inductors (coils) impede signals at higher frequencies more, and admit low frequencies, whereas capacitors do the opposite: capacitors admit high frequencies but impede low frequencies.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] These can be played-off against each other to impede or admit signals based on frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] A simple design for a high-pass filter consists of two 4.7 pF ceramic capacitors and two simple air-core inductor coils (4 turns of 20 AWG copper wire wound using a 6 mm drill bit as a form).
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The design is a symmetric network: The line is cut and the coils are connected from the braid to the core of the coaxial cable ends, while the capacitors bridge the cut, one capacitor connecting core-to-core and the other reconnecting the cut outer shield braids.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] As an extra precaution, a 1.5 MΩ resistor is wired in parallel with the capacitor connecting the shields.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The resistor acts as a “slow leak” on the ground wire that prevents buildup of static electricity on the TV aerial, but is too high a resistance to pass a signal carried along the cable, which operates near 72 Ω.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] The impedance of the capacitors is very large for shortwave signals, below 50 MHz, but for UHF TV signals above 450 MHz their impedance is very small.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] In the opposite sense, the impedance of the coils connecting the inner and outer wires at the lower frequencies is very small, while for the wanted UHF signals the coils have a very high impedance.
[src:braid-breaker/braid-breaker] An even better option is to use both a choke and a high-pass filter, since the filter described above may not be as effective for common-mode currents, which the choke will selectively remove.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A **capacitor** is a device that stores electrical energy by accumulating electric charges on two closely spaced surfaces that are insulated from each other.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] It is a passive electronic component with two terminals.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A capacitor was originally known as a **condenser**, a term still encountered in a few compound names, such as the *condenser microphone*.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Colloquially, a capacitor may be called a ***cap***.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The utility of a capacitor depends on its capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] While some capacitance exists between any two electrical conductors in proximity in a circuit, a capacitor is a component designed specifically to add capacitance to some part of the circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The physical form and construction of practical capacitors vary widely and many types of capacitor are in common use.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Most capacitors contain at least two electrical conductors, often in the form of metallic plates or surfaces separated by a dielectric medium.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A conductor may be a foil, thin film, sintered bead of metal, or an electrolyte.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The nonconducting dielectric acts to increase the capacitor's charge capacity.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Materials commonly used as dielectrics include glass, ceramic, plastic film, paper, mica, air, and oxide layers.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] No current actually flows through a perfect dielectric.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] However, there is a flow of charge through the source circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] If the condition is maintained sufficiently long, the current through the source circuit ceases.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] If a time-varying voltage is applied across the leads of the capacitor, the source experiences an ongoing current due to the charging and discharging cycles of the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are widely used as parts of electrical circuits in many common electrical devices.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Unlike a resistor, an ideal capacitor does not dissipate energy, although real-life capacitors do dissipate a small amount .
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The earliest forms of capacitors were created in the 1740s, when European experimenters discovered that electric charge could be stored in water-filled glass jars that came to be known as Leyden jars.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Today, capacitors are widely used in electronic circuits for blocking direct current while allowing alternating current to pass.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In analog filter networks, they smooth the output of power supplies.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In resonant circuits they tune radios to particular frequencies.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In electric power transmission systems, they stabilize voltage and power flow.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The property of energy storage in capacitors was exploited as dynamic memory in early digital computers, and still is in modern DRAM.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The most common example of natural capacitance are the static charges accumulated between clouds in the sky and the surface of the Earth, where the air between them serves as the dielectric.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This results in bolts of lightning when the breakdown voltage of the air is exceeded.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In October 1745, Ewald Georg von Kleist of Pomerania, Germany, found that charge could be stored by connecting a high-voltage electrostatic generator by a wire to a volume of water in a hand-held glass jar.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist's hand and the water acted as conductors and the jar as a dielectric (although details of the mechanism were incorrectly identified at the time).
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist found that touching the wire resulted in a powerful spark, much more painful than that obtained from an electrostatic machine.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The following year, the Dutch physicist Pieter van Musschenbroek invented a similar capacitor, which was named the Leyden jar, after the University of Leiden where he worked.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Daniel Gralath was the first to combine several jars in parallel to increase the charge storage capacity.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Benjamin Franklin investigated the Leyden jar and came to the conclusion that the charge was stored on the glass, not in the water as others had assumed.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] He also adopted the term "battery", (denoting the increase of power with a row of similar units as in a battery of cannon), subsequently applied to clusters of electrochemical cells.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In 1747, Leyden jars were made by coating the inside and outside of jars with metal foil, leaving a space at the mouth to prevent arcing between the foils.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The earliest unit of capacitance was the jar, equivalent to about 1.11 nanofarads.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] More compact construction methods began to be used, such as a flexible dielectric sheet (like oiled paper) sandwiched between sheets of metal foil, rolled or folded into a small package.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Early capacitors were known as *condensers*, a term that is still occasionally used today, particularly in high power applications, such as automotive systems.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The term became deprecated because of the ambiguous meaning of steam condenser, with *capacitor* being recommended by the British Engineering Standards Association in 1926, although it took several decades for the term to predominate.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Since the beginning of the study of electricity, non-conductive materials like glass, porcelain, paper and mica have been used as insulators.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Decades later, these materials were also well-suited for use as the dielectric for the first capacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Paper capacitors, made by sandwiching a strip of impregnated paper between strips of metal and rolling the result into a cylinder, were commonly used in the late 19th century; their manufacture started in 1876, and they were used from the early 20th century as decoupling capacitors in telephony.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Porcelain was used in the first ceramic capacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In the early years of Marconi's wireless transmitting apparatus, porcelain capacitors were used for high voltage and high frequency application in the transmitters.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] On the receiver side, smaller mica capacitors were used for resonant circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Mica capacitors were invented in 1909 by William Dubilier.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Prior to World War II, mica was the most common dielectric for capacitors in the United States.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Charles Pollak (born Karol Pollak), the inventor of the first electrolytic capacitors, found out that the oxide layer on an aluminum anode remained stable in a neutral or alkaline electrolyte, even when the power was switched off.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] 672,913 for an "Electric liquid capacitor with aluminum electrodes".
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Solid electrolyte tantalum capacitors were invented by Bell Laboratories in the early 1950s as a miniaturized and more reliable low-voltage support capacitor to complement their newly invented transistor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] With the development of plastic materials by organic chemists during the Second World War, the capacitor industry began to replace paper with thinner polymer films.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] One very early development in film capacitors was described in British Patent 587,953 in 1944.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Electric double-layer capacitors (now supercapacitors) were invented in 1957 when H.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Becker developed a "Low voltage electrolytic capacitor with porous carbon electrodes".
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] He believed that the energy was stored as a charge in the carbon pores used in his capacitor as in the pores of the etched foils of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The MOS capacitor was later widely adopted as a storage capacitor in memory chips, and as the basic building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) in image sensor technology.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture, combining a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A capacitor consists of two conductors separated by a non-conductive region.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The non-conductive region can either be a vacuum or an electrical insulator material known as a dielectric.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Examples of dielectric media are glass, air, paper, plastic, ceramic, and even a semiconductor depletion region chemically identical to the conductors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] From Coulomb's law, a charge on one conductor will exert a force on the charge carriers within the other conductor, attracting opposite polarity charge and repelling like polarity charges, thus an opposite polarity charge will be induced on the surface of the other conductor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The conductors thus hold equal and opposite charges on their facing surfaces, and the dielectric develops an electric field.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A capacitance of one farad (1 F) means that one coulomb of charge on each conductor causes a voltage of one volt across the device.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Because the conductors (or plates) are close together, the opposite charges on the conductors attract one another due to their electric fields, allowing the capacitor to store more charge for a given voltage than when the conductors are separated, yielding a larger capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In practical devices, charge build-up sometimes affects the capacitor mechanically, causing its capacitance to vary.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In the hydraulic analogy, voltage is analogous to water pressure and electrical current through a wire is analogous to water flow through a pipe.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A capacitor is like an elastic diaphragm within the pipe.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Although water cannot pass through the diaphragm, it moves as the diaphragm stretches or un-stretches.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In a circuit, a capacitor can behave differently at different time instants.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The simplest model of a capacitor consists of two thin parallel conductive plates each with an area of A separated by a uniform gap of thickness d filled with a dielectric of permittivity ⁠ $\varepsilon$ ⁠.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] It is assumed the gap d is much smaller than the dimensions of the plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This model applies well to many practical capacitors which are constructed of metal sheets separated by a thin layer of insulating dielectric, since manufacturers try to keep the dielectric very uniform in thickness to avoid thin spots which can cause failure of the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This "fringing field" area is approximately the same width as the plate separation, ⁠ d ⁠, and assuming d is small compared to the plate dimensions, it is small enough to be ignored.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] From Gauss's law the magnitude of the electric field between the plates is ⁠ $\textstyle E={\sigma \over \varepsilon }$ ⁠.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Therefore, in a capacitor the highest capacitance is achieved with a high permittivity dielectric material, large plate area, and small separation between the plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Since the area A of the plates increases with the square of the linear dimensions and the separation d increases linearly, the capacitance scales with the linear dimension of a capacitor (⁠ $C\varpropto L$ ⁠), or as the cube root of the volume.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A parallel plate capacitor can only store a finite amount of energy before dielectric breakdown occurs.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The capacitor's dielectric material has a dielectric strength *U*d which sets the capacitor's breakdown voltage at *V* = *V*bd = *U*d*d*.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy is a function of dielectric volume, permittivity, and dielectric strength.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Changing the plate area and the separation between the plates while maintaining the same volume causes no change of the maximum amount of energy that the capacitor can store, so long as the distance between plates remains much smaller than both the length and width of the plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In addition, these equations assume that the electric field is entirely concentrated in the dielectric between the plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In reality there are fringing fields outside the dielectric, for example between the sides of the capacitor plates, which increase the effective capacitance of the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This is sometimes called parasitic capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] For some simple capacitor geometries this additional capacitance term can be calculated analytically.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] It becomes negligibly small when the ratios of plate width to separation and length to separation are large.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] For n number of plates in a capacitor, the total capacitance would be $C=\varepsilon _{o}{\frac {A}{d}}(n-1)$ where ${\textstyle C={\frac {\varepsilon _{o}A}{d}}}$ is the capacitance for a single plate and n is the number of interleaved plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] As shown to the figure on the right, the interleaved plates can be seen as parallel plates connected to each other.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Every pair of adjacent plates acts as a separate capacitor; the number of pairs is always one less than the number of plates, hence the $(n-1)$ multiplier.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] To increase the charge and voltage on a capacitor, work must be done by an external power source to move charge from the negative to the positive plate against the opposing force of the electric field.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] If the voltage on the capacitor is ⁠ V ⁠, the work $\mathrm {d} W$ required to move a small increment of charge $\mathrm {d} q$ from the negative to the positive plate is ⁠ $\mathrm {d} W=V\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} q$ ⁠.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The energy is stored in the increased electric field between the plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This potential energy will remain in the capacitor until the charge is removed.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] If charge is allowed to move back from the positive to the negative plate, for example by connecting a circuit with resistance between the plates, the charge moving under the influence of the electric field will do work on the external circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] If the gap between the capacitor plates d is constant, as in the parallel plate model above, the electric field between the plates will be uniform (neglecting fringing fields) and will have a constant value ⁠ $E=V/d$ ⁠.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The current $I(t)$ through any component in an electric circuit is defined as the rate of flow of a charge $Q(t)$ passing through it.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Actual charges – electrons – cannot pass through the dielectric of an *ideal* capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Rather, one electron accumulates on the negative plate for each one that leaves the positive plate, resulting in an electron depletion and consequent positive charge on one electrode that is equal and opposite to the accumulated negative charge on the other.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Thus the charge on the electrodes is equal to the integral of the current as well as proportional to the voltage, as discussed above.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] As with any antiderivative, a constant of integration is added to represent the initial voltage ⁠ $V(t_{0})$ ⁠).
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] for C independent of time, voltage and electric charge.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The dual of the capacitor is the inductor, which stores energy in a magnetic field rather than an electric field.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Its current-voltage relation is obtained by exchanging current and voltage in the capacitor equations and replacing C with the inductance L.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A series circuit containing only a resistor, a capacitor, a switch and a constant DC source of voltage *V*0 is known as a *charging circuit*.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] At *t* = 0, the voltage across the capacitor is zero and the voltage across the resistor is *V*0.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The initial current is then ⁠ $\textstyle I(0)={V_{0} \over R}$ ⁠.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] As the capacitor reaches equilibrium with the source voltage, the voltages across the resistor and the current through the entire circuit decay exponentially.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In the case of a *discharging* capacitor, the capacitor's initial voltage (*V*Ci) replaces *V*0.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Impedance, the vector sum of reactance and resistance, describes the phase difference and the ratio of amplitudes between sinusoidally varying voltage and sinusoidally varying current at a given frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Fourier analysis allows any signal to be constructed from a spectrum of frequencies, whence the circuit's reaction to the various frequencies may be found.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ $-j$ ⁠ phase indicates that the AC voltage ⁠ $V=ZI$ ⁠ lags the AC current by 90°: the positive current phase corresponds to increasing voltage as the capacitor charges; zero current corresponds to instantaneous constant voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Impedance decreases with increasing capacitance and increasing frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This implies that a higher-frequency signal or a larger capacitor results in a lower voltage amplitude per current amplitude – an AC "short circuit" or AC coupling.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Conversely, for very low frequencies, the reactance is high, so that a capacitor is nearly an open circuit in AC analysis – those frequencies have been "filtered out".
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are different from resistors and inductors in that the impedance is *inversely* proportional to the defining characteristic; i.e., capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A capacitor connected to an alternating voltage source has a displacement current to flowing through it.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] At ⁠ $\sin(\omega t)=-1$ ⁠, the capacitor has a maximum (or peak) current whereby ⁠ $I_{0}=\omega CV_{0}$ ⁠.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In this situation, the current is out of phase with the voltage by ⁠ $\textstyle +{\pi \over 2}$ ⁠ radians or +90 degrees, i.e. the current leads the voltage by 90°.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Capacitors in a parallel configuration each have the same applied voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Charge is apportioned among them by capacitance value.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Connected in series, the schematic diagram reveals that the separation distance, not the plate area, adds up.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The capacitors each store instantaneous charge build-up equal to that of every other capacitor in the series.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The total voltage difference from end to end is apportioned to each capacitor according to the inverse of its capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are combined in series to achieve a higher working voltage, for example for smoothing a high voltage power supply.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The voltage ratings, which are based on plate separation, add up, if capacitance and leakage currents for each capacitor are identical.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In such an application, on occasion, series strings are connected in parallel, forming a matrix.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The goal is to maximize the energy storage of the network without overloading any capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] For high-energy storage with capacitors in series, some safety considerations must be applied to ensure one capacitor failing and leaking current does not apply too much voltage to the other series capacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Series connection is also sometimes used to adapt polarized electrolytic capacitors for bipolar AC use.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] (Note that this is only correct if all capacitance values are equal).
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In practice, capacitors deviate from the ideal capacitor equation in several aspects.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Some of these, such as leakage current and parasitic effects are linear, or can be analyzed as nearly linear, and can be accounted for by adding virtual components to form an equivalent circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The usual methods of network analysis can then be applied.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In other cases, such as with breakdown voltage, the effect is non-linear and ordinary (normal, e.g., linear) network analysis cannot be used, the effect must be considered separately.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Yet another group of artifacts may exist, including temperature dependence, that may be linear but invalidates the assumption in the analysis that capacitance is a constant.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Finally, combined parasitic effects such as inherent inductance, resistance, or dielectric losses can exhibit non-uniform behavior at varying frequencies of operation.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Above a particular electric field strength, known as the dielectric strength ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {ds} }$ ⁠, the dielectric in a capacitor becomes conductive.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy that can be stored safely in a capacitor is limited by the breakdown voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Exceeding this voltage can result in a short circuit between the plates, which can often cause permanent damage to the dielectric, plates, or both.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Due to the scaling of capacitance and breakdown voltage with dielectric thickness, all capacitors made with a particular dielectric have approximately equal maximum energy density, to the extent that the dielectric dominates their volume.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] For air dielectric capacitors the breakdown field strength is of the order 2–5 MV/m (or equivalently in kilovolts per millimeter); for mica the breakdown is 100–300 MV/m; for oil, 15–25 MV/m; it can be much less when other materials are used for the dielectric.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The dielectric is used in very thin layers and so absolute breakdown voltage of capacitors is limited.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Typical ratings for capacitors used for general electronics applications range from a few volts to 1 kilovolt.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] As the voltage increases, the dielectric must be thicker, making high-voltage capacitors larger per capacitance than those rated for lower voltages.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The breakdown voltage is critically affected by factors such as the geometry of the capacitor conductive parts; sharp edges or points increase the electric field strength at that point and can lead to a local breakdown.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Once this starts to happen, the breakdown quickly tracks through the dielectric until it reaches the opposite plate, leaving carbon behind and causing a short (or relatively low resistance) circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The results can be explosive, as the short in the capacitor draws current from the surrounding circuitry and dissipates the energy.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] However, in capacitors with particular dielectrics and thin metal electrodes, shorts are not formed after breakdown.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] It happens because a metal melts or evaporates in a breakdown vicinity, isolating it from the rest of the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The usual breakdown route is that the field strength becomes large enough to pull electrons in the dielectric from their atoms thus causing conduction.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Other scenarios are possible, such as impurities in the dielectric, and, if the dielectric is of a crystalline nature, imperfections in the crystal structure can result in an avalanche breakdown as seen in semi-conductor devices.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Breakdown voltage is also affected by pressure, humidity and temperature.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] An ideal capacitor only stores and releases electrical energy, without dissipation.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] As frequency increases, the capacitive impedance (a negative reactance) reduces, so the dielectric's conductance becomes less important and the series components become more significant.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Thus, a simplified RLC series model valid for a large frequency range simply treats the capacitor as being in series with an equivalent series inductance ${\text{ESL}}$ and a frequency-dependent *equivalent series resistance* ${\text{ESR}}$ , which varies little with frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Unlike the previous model, this model is not valid at DC and very low frequencies where $G_{\text{dielectric}}$ is relevant.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Inductive reactance increases with frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Because its sign is positive, it counteracts the capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] At the RLC circuit's natural frequency $\omega _{0}{=}{\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {{\text{ESL}}\cdot {\text{C}}}}}$ , the inductance perfectly cancels the capacitance, so total reactance is zero.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Since the total impedance at $\omega _{0}$ is just the real-value of ${\text{ESR}}$ , average power dissipation reaches its maximum of ⁠VRMS2/ESR⁠, where VRMS is the root mean square (RMS) voltage across the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] At even higher frequencies, the inductive impedance dominates, so the capacitor undesirably behaves instead like an inductor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] High-frequency engineering involves accounting for the inductance of all connections and components.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ Q ⁠ factor is a measure of its efficiency: the higher the ⁠ Q ⁠ factor of the capacitor, the closer it approaches the behavior of an ideal capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Ripple current is the AC component of an applied source (often a switched-mode power supply) whose frequency may be constant or varying.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Ripple current causes heat to be generated within the capacitor due to the dielectric losses caused by the changing field strength together with the current flow across the slightly resistive supply lines or the electrolyte in the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The equivalent series resistance (ESR) is the amount of internal series resistance one would add to a perfect capacitor to model this.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Some types of capacitors, primarily tantalum and aluminum electrolytic capacitors, as well as some film capacitors have a specified rating value for maximum ripple current.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The capacitance of certain capacitors decreases as the component ages.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In ceramic capacitors, this is caused by degradation of the dielectric.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The type of dielectric, ambient operating and storage temperatures are the most significant aging factors, while the operating voltage usually has a smaller effect, i.e., usual capacitor design is to minimize voltage coefficient.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The aging process may be reversed by heating the component above the Curie point.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Aging is fastest near the beginning of life of the component, and the device stabilizes over time.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors age as the electrolyte evaporates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In contrast with ceramic capacitors, this occurs towards the end of life of the component.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Temperature dependence of capacitance is usually expressed in parts per million (ppm) per °C.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] It can usually be taken as a broadly linear function but can be noticeably non-linear at the temperature extremes.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The temperature coefficient may be positive or negative, depending mostly on the dielectric material.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Some, designated C0G/NP0, but called **NPO**, have a somewhat negative coefficient at one temperature, positive at another, and zero in between.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Such components may be specified for temperature-critical circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Capacitors, especially ceramic capacitors, and older designs such as paper capacitors, can absorb sound waves resulting in a microphonic effect.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Vibration moves the plates, causing the capacitance to vary, in turn inducing AC current.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Some dielectrics also generate piezoelectricity.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The resulting interference is especially problematic in audio applications, potentially causing feedback or unintended recording.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In the reverse microphonic effect, the varying electric field between the capacitor plates exerts a physical force, moving them as a speaker.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This can generate audible sound, but drains energy and stresses the dielectric and the electrolyte, if any.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Current reversal occurs when the current changes direction.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is the change of polarity in a circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Reversal is generally described as the percentage of the maximum rated voltage that reverses polarity.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits, this is usually less than 100%, often in the range of 0 to 90%, whereas AC circuits experience 100% reversal.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits and pulsed circuits, current and voltage reversal are affected by the damping of the system.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is encountered in RLC circuits that are underdamped.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage reverse direction, forming a harmonic oscillator between the inductance and capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage tends to oscillate and may reverse direction several times, with each peak being lower than the previous, until the system reaches an equilibrium.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In comparison, critically damped or overdamped systems usually do not experience a voltage reversal.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Reversal is also encountered in AC circuits, where the peak current is equal in each direction.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] For maximum life, capacitors usually need to be able to handle the maximum amount of reversal that a system may experience.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] An AC circuit experiences 100% voltage reversal, while underdamped DC circuits experience less than 100%.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Reversal creates excess electric fields in the dielectric, causes excess heating of both the dielectric and the conductors, and can dramatically shorten the life expectancy of the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Reversal ratings often affect the design considerations for the capacitor, from the choice of dielectric materials and voltage ratings to the types of internal connections used.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Capacitors made with any type of dielectric material show some level of "dielectric absorption" or "soakage".
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] On discharging a capacitor and disconnecting it, after a short time it may develop a voltage due to hysteresis in the dielectric.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This effect is objectionable in applications such as precision sample and hold circuits or timing circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The level of absorption depends on many factors, from design considerations to charging time, since the absorption is a time-dependent process.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] However, the primary factor is the type of dielectric material.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Capacitors such as tantalum electrolytic or polysulfone film exhibit relatively high absorption, while polystyrene or Teflon allow very small levels of absorption.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In some capacitors where dangerous voltages and energies exist, such as in flashtubes, television sets, microwave ovens and defibrillators, the dielectric absorption can recharge the capacitor to hazardous voltages after it has been shorted or discharged.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Any capacitor containing over 10 joules of energy is generally considered hazardous, while 50 joules or higher is potentially lethal.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A capacitor may regain anywhere from 0.01 to 20% of its original charge over a period of several minutes, allowing a seemingly safe capacitor to become surprisingly dangerous.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] No material is a perfect insulator, thus all dielectrics allow some small level of current to leak through, which can be measured with a megohmmeter.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Leakage is equivalent to a resistor in parallel with the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Constant exposure to factors such as heat, mechanical stress, or humidity can cause the dielectric to deteriorate resulting in excessive leakage, a problem often seen in older vacuum tube circuits, particularly where oiled paper and foil capacitors were used.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In many vacuum tube circuits, interstage coupling capacitors are used to conduct a varying signal from the plate of one tube to the grid circuit of the next stage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] A leaky capacitor can cause the grid circuit voltage to be raised from its normal bias setting, causing excessive current or signal distortion in the downstream tube.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] In power amplifiers this can cause the plates to glow red, or current limiting resistors to overheat, even fail.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Similar considerations apply to component fabricated solid-state (transistor) amplifiers, but, owing to lower heat production and the use of modern polyester dielectric-barriers, this once-common problem has become relatively rare.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors are *conditioned* when manufactured by applying a voltage sufficient to initiate the proper internal chemical state.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] This state is maintained by regular use of the equipment.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] If a system using electrolytic capacitors is unused for a long period of time it can lose its conditioning.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Sometimes they fail with a short circuit when next operated.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] All capacitors have varying lifespans, depending upon their construction, operational conditions, and environmental conditions.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Solid-state ceramic capacitors generally have very long lives under normal use, which has little dependency on factors such as vibration or ambient temperature, but factors like humidity, mechanical stress, and fatigue play a primary role in their failure.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Some capacitors may experience a gradual loss of capacitance, increased leakage or an increase in equivalent series resistance (ESR), while others may fail suddenly or even catastrophically.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] For example, metal-film capacitors are more prone to damage from stress and humidity, but will self-heal when a breakdown in the dielectric occurs.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The formation of a glow discharge at the point of failure prevents arcing by vaporizing the metallic film in that spot, neutralizing any short circuit with minimal loss in capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] When enough pinholes accumulate in the film, a total failure occurs in a metal-film capacitor, generally happening suddenly without warning.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors generally have the shortest lifespans.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors are affected very little by vibration or humidity, but factors such as ambient and operational temperatures play a large role in their failure, which gradually occur as an increase in ESR (up to 300%) and as much as a 20% decrease in capacitance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] The capacitors contain electrolytes which will eventually diffuse through the seals and evaporate.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] An increase in temperature also increases internal pressure, and increases the reaction rate of the chemicals.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] Manufacturers often use this equation to supply an expected lifespan, in hours, for electrolytic capacitors when used at their designed operating temperature, which is affected by both ambient temperature, ESR, and ripple current.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p01] However, these ideal conditions may not exist in every use.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Practical capacitors are available commercially in many different forms.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The type of internal dielectric, the structure of the plates and the device packaging all strongly affect the characteristics of the capacitor, and its applications.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Values available range from very low (picofarad range; while arbitrarily low values are in principle possible, stray (parasitic) capacitance in any circuit is the limiting factor) to about 5 kF supercapacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Above approximately 1 microfarad electrolytic capacitors are usually used because of their small size and low cost compared with other types, unless their relatively poor stability, life and polarised nature make them unsuitable.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Very high capacity supercapacitors use a porous carbon-based electrode material.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have a dielectric spacer, which increases their capacitance compared to air or a vacuum.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In order to maximise the charge that a capacitor can hold, the dielectric material needs to have as high a permittivity as possible, while also having as high a breakdown voltage as possible.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The dielectric also needs to have as low a loss with frequency as possible.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] However, low value capacitors are available with a high vacuum between their plates to allow extremely high voltage operation and low losses.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Variable capacitors with their plates open to the atmosphere were commonly used in radio tuning circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Later designs use polymer foil dielectric between the moving and stationary plates, with no significant air space between the plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Several solid dielectrics are available, including paper, plastic, glass, mica and ceramic.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Paper was used extensively in older capacitors and offers relatively high voltage performance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] However, paper absorbs moisture, and has been largely replaced by plastic film capacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Large plastic film capacitors are used extensively in suppression circuits, motor start circuits, and power-factor correction circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are generally small, cheap and useful for high frequency applications, although their capacitance varies strongly with voltage and temperature and they age poorly.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] They can also suffer from the piezoelectric effect.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are broadly categorized as class 1 dielectrics, which have predictable variation of capacitance with temperature or class 2 dielectrics, which can operate at higher voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Modern multilayer ceramics are usually quite small, but some types have inherently wide value tolerances, microphonic issues, and are usually physically brittle.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Glass and mica capacitors are extremely reliable, stable and tolerant to high temperatures and voltages, but are too expensive for most mainstream applications.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors use an aluminum or tantalum plate with an oxide dielectric layer.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The second electrode is a liquid electrolyte, connected to the circuit by another foil plate.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors offer very high capacitance but suffer from poor tolerances, high instability, gradual loss of capacitance especially when subjected to heat, and high leakage current.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Poor quality capacitors may leak electrolyte, which is harmful to printed circuit boards.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The conductivity of the electrolyte drops at low temperatures, which increases equivalent series resistance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] While widely used for power-supply conditioning, poor high-frequency characteristics make them unsuitable for many applications.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors suffer from self-degradation if unused for a period (around a year), and when full power is applied may short circuit, permanently damaging the capacitor and usually blowing a fuse or causing failure of rectifier diodes.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] For example, in older equipment, this may cause arcing in rectifier tubes.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] They can be restored before use by gradually applying the operating voltage, often performed on antique vacuum tube equipment over a period of thirty minutes by using a variable transformer to supply AC power.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The use of this technique may be less satisfactory for some solid state equipment, which may be damaged by operation below its normal power range, requiring that the power supply first be isolated from the consuming circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Such remedies may not be applicable to modern high-frequency power supplies as these produce full output voltage even with reduced input.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Tantalum capacitors offer better frequency and temperature characteristics than aluminum, but higher dielectric absorption and leakage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Polymer capacitors (OS-CON, OC-CON, KO, AO) use solid conductive polymer (or polymerized organic semiconductor) as electrolyte and offer longer life and lower ESR at higher cost than standard electrolytic capacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A feedthrough capacitor is a component that, while not serving as its main use, has capacitance and is used to conduct signals through a conductive sheet.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Several other types of capacitor are available for specialist applications.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors store large amounts of energy.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors made from carbon aerogel, carbon nanotubes, or highly porous electrode materials, offer extremely high capacitance (up to 5 kF as of 2010) and can be used in some applications instead of rechargeable batteries.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Alternating current capacitors are specifically designed to work on line (mains) voltage AC power circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] They are commonly used in electric motor circuits and are often designed to handle large currents, so they tend to be physically large.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] They are usually ruggedly packaged, often in metal cases that can be easily grounded/earthed.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] They also are designed with direct current breakdown voltages of at least five times the maximum AC voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The dielectric constant for a number of very useful dielectrics changes as a function of the applied electrical field, for example ferroelectric materials, so the capacitance for these devices is more complex.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] This field polarizes the dielectric, which polarization, in the case of a ferroelectric, is a nonlinear *S*-shaped function of the electric field, which, in the case of a large area parallel plate device, translates into a capacitance that is a nonlinear function of the voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Corresponding to the voltage-dependent capacitance, to charge the capacitor to voltage V an integral relation is found: $Q=\int _{0}^{V}C(V)\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} V$ which agrees with *Q* = *CV* only when C does not depend on voltage V.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The nonlinear capacitance of a microscope probe scanned along a ferroelectric surface is used to study the domain structure of ferroelectric materials.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Another example of voltage dependent capacitance occurs in semiconductor devices such as semiconductor diodes, where the voltage dependence stems not from a change in dielectric constant but in a voltage dependence of the spacing between the charges on the two sides of the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] This effect is intentionally exploited in diode-like devices known as varicaps.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] If a capacitor is driven with a time-varying voltage that changes rapidly enough, at some frequency the polarization of the dielectric cannot follow the voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] As an example of the origin of this mechanism, the internal microscopic dipoles contributing to the dielectric constant cannot move instantly, and so as frequency of an applied alternating voltage increases, the dipole response is limited and the dielectric constant diminishes.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A changing dielectric constant with frequency is referred to as dielectric dispersion, and is governed by dielectric relaxation processes, such as Debye relaxation.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] indicating the lag in response by the time dependence of *εr*, calculated in principle from an underlying microscopic analysis, for example, of the dipole behavior in the dielectric.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] See, for example, linear response function.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The integral extends over the entire past history up to the present time.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] where *ε*r(*ω*) is now a complex function, with an imaginary part related to absorption of energy from the field by the medium.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The capacitance, being proportional to the dielectric constant, also exhibits this frequency behavior.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] (Measurement "without the dielectric" in principle means measurement in free space, an unattainable goal inasmuch as even the quantum vacuum is predicted to exhibit nonideal behavior, such as dichroism.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Using this measurement method, the dielectric constant may exhibit a resonance at certain frequencies corresponding to characteristic response frequencies (excitation energies) of contributors to the dielectric constant.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] These resonances are the basis for a number of experimental techniques for detecting defects.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The *conductance method* measures absorption as a function of frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Alternatively, the time response of the capacitance can be used directly, as in *deep-level transient spectroscopy*.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Another example of frequency dependent capacitance occurs with MOS capacitors, where the slow generation of minority carriers means that at high frequencies the capacitance measures only the majority carrier response, while at low frequencies both types of carrier respond.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] At optical frequencies, in semiconductors the dielectric constant exhibits structure related to the band structure of the solid.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Sophisticated modulation spectroscopy measurement methods based upon modulating the crystal structure by pressure or by other stresses and observing the related changes in absorption or reflection of light have advanced our knowledge of these materials.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The arrangement of plates and dielectric has many variations in different styles depending on the desired ratings of the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] For small values of capacitance (microfarads and less), ceramic disks use metallic coatings, with wire leads bonded to the coating.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Larger values can be made by multiple stacks of plates and disks.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Larger value capacitors usually use a metal foil or metal film layer deposited on the surface of a dielectric film to make the plates, and a dielectric film of impregnated paper or plastic – these are rolled up to save space.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] To reduce the series resistance and inductance for long plates, the plates and dielectric are staggered so that connection is made at the common edge of the rolled-up plates, not at the ends of the foil or metalized film strips that comprise the plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The assembly is encased to prevent moisture entering the dielectric – early radio equipment used a cardboard tube sealed with wax.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Modern paper or film dielectric capacitors are dipped in a hard thermoplastic.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Large capacitors for high-voltage use may have the roll form compressed to fit into a rectangular metal case, with bolted terminals and bushings for connections.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The dielectric in larger capacitors is often impregnated with a liquid to improve its properties.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may have their connecting leads arranged in many configurations, for example axially or radially.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] "Axial" means that the leads are on a common axis, typically the axis of the capacitor's cylindrical body – the leads extend from opposite ends.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Radial leads are rarely aligned along radii of the body's circle, so the term is conventional.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The leads (until bent) are usually in planes parallel to that of the flat body of the capacitor, and extend in the same direction; they are often parallel as manufactured.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Small, cheap discoidal ceramic capacitors have existed from the 1930s onward, and remain in widespread use.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] After the 1980s, surface mount packages for capacitors have been widely used.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] These packages are extremely small and lack connecting leads, allowing them to be soldered directly onto the surface of printed circuit boards.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Surface mount components avoid undesirable high-frequency effects due to the leads and simplify automated assembly, although manual handling is made difficult due to their small size.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Mechanically controlled variable capacitors allow the plate spacing to be adjusted, for example by rotating or sliding a set of movable plates into alignment with a set of stationary plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Low cost variable capacitors squeeze together alternating layers of aluminum and plastic with a screw.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Electrical control of capacitance is achievable with varactors (or varicaps), which are reverse-biased semiconductor diodes whose depletion region width varies with applied voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] They are used in phase-locked loops, amongst other applications.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have designations printed on their bodies to indicate their electrical characteristics.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors, such as electrolytic types usually display the capacitance as value with explicit unit, for example, *220 μF*.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] For typographical reasons, some manufacturers print *MF* on capacitors to indicate microfarads (μF).
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Smaller capacitors, such as ceramic types, often use a shorthand-notation consisting of three digits and an optional letter, where the digits (*XYZ*) denote the capacitance in picofarad (pF), calculated as *XY* × 10*Z*, and the letter indicating the tolerance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Common tolerances are ±5%, ±10%, and ±20%, denoted as J, K, and M, respectively.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A capacitor may also be labeled with its working voltage, temperature, and other relevant characteristics.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Example: A capacitor labeled or designated as *473K 330V* has a capacitance of 47×103 pF = 47 nF (±10%) with a maximum working voltage of 330 V.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The working voltage of a capacitor is nominally the highest voltage that may be applied across it without undue risk of breaking down the dielectric layer.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The code consists of an uppercase letter denoting the two significant digits of the value followed by a digit indicating the multiplier.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The EIA standard also defines a number of lowercase letters to specify a number of values not found in E24.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The RKM code following IEC 60062 and BS 1852 is a notation to state a capacitor's value in a circuit diagram.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] It avoids using a decimal separator and replaces the decimal separator with the SI prefix symbol for the particular value (and the letter F for weight 1).
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The code is also used for part markings.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In texts prior to the 1960s and on some capacitor packages until more recently, obsolete capacitance units were utilized in electronic books, magazines, and electronics catalogs.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The old units "mfd" and "mf" meant *microfarad* (μF); and the old units "mmfd", "mmf", "uuf", "μμf", "pfd" meant *picofarad* (pF); but they are rarely used any more.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Also, "Micromicrofarad" or "micro-microfarad" are obsolete units that are found in some older texts that is equivalent to *picofarad* (pF).
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can store electric energy when disconnected from its charging circuit, so it can be used like a temporary battery, or like other types of rechargeable energy storage system.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are commonly used in electronic devices to maintain power supply while batteries are being changed.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can facilitate conversion of kinetic energy of charged particles into electric energy and store it.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] There are tradeoffs between capacitors and batteries as storage devices.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Without external resistors or inductors, capacitors can generally release their stored energy in a very short time compared to batteries.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Conversely, batteries can hold a far greater charge per their size.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Conventional capacitors provide less than 360 joules per kilogram of specific energy, whereas a conventional alkaline battery has a density of 590 kJ/kg.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] There is an intermediate solution: supercapacitors, which can accept and deliver charge much faster than batteries, and tolerate many more charge and discharge cycles than rechargeable batteries.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] They are, however, 10 times larger than conventional batteries for a given charge.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] On the other hand, it has been shown that the amount of charge stored in the dielectric layer of the thin film capacitor can be equal to, or can even exceed, the amount of charge stored on its plates.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In car audio systems, large capacitors store energy for the amplifier to use on demand.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Also, for a flash tube, a capacitor is used to hold the high voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In the 1930s, John Atanasoff applied the principle of energy storage in capacitors to construct dynamic digital memories for the first binary computers that used electron tubes for logic.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Pulsed power is used in many applications to increase the power intensity (watts) of a volume of energy (joules) by releasing that volume within a very short time.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Pulses in the nanosecond range and powers in the gigawatts are achievable.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Short pulses often require specially constructed, low-inductance, high-voltage capacitors that are often used in large groups (*capacitor banks*) to supply huge pulses of current for many pulsed power applications.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] These include electromagnetic forming, Marx generators, pulsed lasers (especially TEA lasers), pulse forming networks, radar, fusion research, and particle accelerators.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Large capacitor banks (reservoir) are used as energy sources for the exploding-bridgewire detonators or slapper detonators in nuclear weapons and other specialty weapons.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Experimental work is under way using banks of capacitors as power sources for electromagnetic armour and electromagnetic railguns and coilguns.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Reservoir capacitors are used in power supplies where they smooth the output of a full or half wave rectifier.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] They can also be used in charge pump circuits as the energy storage element in the generation of higher voltages than the input voltage.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are connected in parallel with the power circuits of most electronic devices and larger systems (such as factories) to shunt away and conceal current fluctuations from the primary power source to provide a "clean" power supply for signal or control circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Audio equipment, for example, uses several capacitors in this way, to shunt away power line hum before it gets into the signal circuitry.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The capacitors act as a local reserve for the DC power source, and bypass AC currents from the power supply.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] This is used in car audio applications, when a stiffening capacitor compensates for the inductance and resistance of the leads to the lead–acid car battery.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In electric power distribution, capacitors are used for power-factor correction.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors often come as three capacitors connected as a three phase load.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Usually, the values of these capacitors are not given in farads but rather as a reactive power in volt-amperes reactive (var).
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The purpose is to counteract inductive loading from devices like electric motors and transmission lines to make the load appear to be mostly resistive.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Individual motor or lamp loads may have capacitors for power-factor correction, or larger sets of capacitors (usually with automatic switching devices) may be installed at a load center within a building or in a large utility substation.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Because capacitors pass AC but block DC signals (when charged up to the applied DC voltage), they are often used to separate the AC and DC components of a signal.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] This method is known as *AC coupling* or "capacitive coupling".
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Here, a large value of capacitance, whose value need not be accurately controlled, but whose reactance is small at the signal frequency, is employed.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A decoupling capacitor is a capacitor used to protect one part of a circuit from the effect of another, for instance to suppress noise or transients.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Noise caused by other circuit elements is shunted through the capacitor, reducing the effect they have on the rest of the circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] It is most commonly used between the power supply and ground.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] An alternative name is *bypass capacitor* as it is used to bypass the power supply or other high impedance component of a circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Decoupling capacitors need not always be discrete components.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in these applications may be built into a printed circuit board, between the various layers.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] These are often referred to as embedded capacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The layers in the board contributing to the capacitive properties also function as power and ground planes, and have a dielectric in between them, enabling them to operate as a parallel plate capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] When an inductive circuit is opened, the current through the inductance collapses quickly, creating a large voltage across the open circuit of the switch or relay.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] If the inductance is large enough, the energy may generate a spark, causing the contact points to oxidize, deteriorate, or sometimes weld together, or destroying a solid-state switch.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A snubber capacitor across the newly opened circuit creates a path for this impulse to bypass the contact points, thereby preserving their life; these were commonly found in contact breaker ignition systems, for instance.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Similarly, in smaller scale circuits, the spark may not be enough to damage the switch but may still radiate undesirable radio frequency interference (RFI), which a filter capacitor absorbs.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Snubber capacitors are usually employed with a low-value resistor in series, to dissipate energy and minimize RFI.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Such resistor-capacitor combinations are available in a single package.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are also used in parallel with interrupting units of a high-voltage circuit breaker to equally distribute the voltage between these units.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In schematic diagrams, a capacitor used primarily for DC charge storage is often drawn vertically in circuit diagrams with the lower, more negative, plate drawn as an arc.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The straight plate indicates the positive terminal of the device, if it is polarized (see electrolytic capacitor).
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In single phase squirrel cage motors, the primary winding within the motor housing is not capable of starting a rotational motion on the rotor, but is capable of sustaining one.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] To start the motor, a secondary "start" winding has a series non-polarized *starting capacitor* to introduce a lead in the sinusoidal current.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] When the secondary (start) winding is placed at an angle with respect to the primary (run) winding, a rotating electric field is created.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The force of the rotational field is not constant, but is sufficient to start the rotor spinning.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] When the rotor comes close to operating speed, a centrifugal switch (or current-sensitive relay in series with the main winding) disconnects the capacitor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The start capacitor is typically mounted to the side of the motor housing.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] These are called capacitor-start motors, that have relatively high starting torque.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Typically they can have up-to four times as much starting torque as a split-phase motor and are used on applications such as compressors, pressure washers and any small device requiring high starting torques.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitor-run induction motors have a permanently connected phase-shifting capacitor in series with a second winding.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The motor is much like a two-phase induction motor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Motor-starting capacitors are typically non-polarized electrolytic types, while running capacitors are conventional paper or plastic film dielectric types.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The energy stored in a capacitor can be used to represent information, either in binary form, as in DRAMs, or in analogue form, as in analog sampled filters and CCDs.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors can be used in analog circuits as components of integrators or more complex filters and in negative feedback loop stabilization.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Signal processing circuits also use capacitors to integrate a current signal.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors and inductors are applied together in tuned circuits to select information in particular frequency bands.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] For example, radio receivers rely on variable capacitors to tune the station frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Speakers use passive analog crossovers, and analog equalizers use capacitors to select different audio bands.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The resonant frequency *f* of a tuned circuit is a function of the inductance (*L*) and capacitance (*C*) in series, and is given by: $f={\frac {1}{2\pi {\sqrt {LC}}}}$ where L is in henries and C is in farads.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors are designed to maintain a fixed physical structure.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] However, various factors can change the structure of the capacitor, and the resulting change in capacitance can be used to sense those factors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with an exposed and porous dielectric can be used to measure humidity in air.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] ; as the fuel covers more of a pair of plates, the circuit capacitance increases.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Squeezing the dielectric can change a capacitor at a few tens of bar pressure sufficiently that it can be used as a pressure sensor.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A selected, but otherwise standard, polymer dielectric capacitor, when immersed in a compatible gas or liquid, can work usefully as a very low cost pressure sensor up to many hundreds of bar.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with a flexible plate can be used to measure strain or pressure.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] use pressure-sensing diaphragms, which form a capacitor plate of an oscillator circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] , where one plate is moved by air pressure, relative to the fixed position of the other plate.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] capacitors etched on a chip to measure the magnitude and direction of the acceleration vector.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] deployment, and in many other applications.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] musical instrument by moving their hand since this changes the effective capacitance between the user's hand and the antenna.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] are used on many consumer electronic products.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can possess spring-like qualities in an oscillator circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In the image example, a capacitor acts to influence the biasing voltage at the npn transistor's base.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The resistance values of the voltage-divider resistors and the capacitance value of the capacitor together control the oscillatory frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] A light-emitting capacitor is made from a dielectric that uses phosphorescence to produce light.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] If one of the conductive plates is made with a transparent material, the light is visible.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Light-emitting capacitors are used in the construction of electroluminescent panels, for applications such as backlighting for laptop computers.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] In this case, the entire panel is a capacitor used for the purpose of generating light.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] The hazards posed by a capacitor are usually determined by the amount of energy stored, which can cause electrical burns or heart fibrillation.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Factors such as voltage and chassis material are of secondary consideration, which are more related to how easily a shock can be initiated rather than how much damage can occur.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Shocks over ten joules generally damage skin, and are considered hazardous.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Any capacitor that can store 50 joules or more is considered potentially lethal.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may retain a charge long after power is removed from a circuit; this charge can cause dangerous or fatal shocks or damage connected equipment.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] For example, the flash of a disposable camera has a photoflash capacitor that may contain over 15 joules of energy and be charged to over 300 volts.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Service procedures for electronic devices usually include instructions to discharge large or high-voltage capacitors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have built-in discharge resistors to dissipate stored energy to a safe level within a few seconds after power is removed.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors are stored with the terminals shorted, as protection from potentially dangerous voltages due to dielectric absorption or from transient voltages the capacitor may pick up from static charges or passing weather events.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Some old, large oil-filled paper or plastic film capacitors contain polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) which can leak into groundwater from landfills.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors containing PCBs were labelled as containing "Askarel" and several other trade names.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] PCB-filled paper capacitors are found in pre-1975 fluorescent lamp ballasts, and other applications.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors may be sealed in a metal can with ceramic feed-through connectors.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may catastrophically fail when subjected to voltages or currents beyond their rating, or in case of polarized capacitors, applied in a reverse polarity.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Failures may create arcing that heats and vaporizes the dielectric fluid, causing a build up of pressurized gas that may result in swelling, rupture, or an explosion.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have vents or similar mechanism to release of pressure in the event of failure.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in RF or sustained high-current applications can overheat, especially in the center of the capacitor rolls.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used within high-energy capacitor banks can violently explode when a short in one capacitor causes sudden dumping of energy stored in the rest of the bank into the failing unit.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] High voltage vacuum capacitors can generate soft X-rays even during normal operation.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] Proper containment, fusing, and preventive maintenance can help to minimize these hazards.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors may benefit from a pre-charge to limit in-rush currents at power-up of high voltage direct current (HVDC) circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/capacitor-p02] This extends the life of the component and may mitigate high-voltage hazards.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] In electronics, a **choke** is an inductor used to block higher-frequency alternating currents (AC) while passing direct current (DC) and lower-frequency ACs in a circuit.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] A choke usually consists of a coil of insulated wire often wound on a magnetic core, although some consist of a doughnut-shaped ferrite bead strung on a wire.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] The choke's impedance increases with frequency.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Its low electrical resistance passes both AC and DC with little power loss, but its reactance limits the amount of AC passed.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] The name comes from blocking—"choking"—high frequencies while passing low frequencies.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] It is a functional name; the name "choke" is used if an inductor is used for blocking or decoupling higher frequencies, but the component is simply called an "inductor" if used in electronic filters or tuned circuits.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Inductors designed for use as chokes are usually distinguished by not having low-loss construction (high Q factor) required in inductors used in tuned circuits and filtering applications.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Audio frequency chokes usually have ferromagnetic cores to increase their inductance.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] They are often constructed similarly to transformers, with laminated iron cores and an air gap.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] The iron core increases the inductance for a given volume of the core.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Chokes were frequently used in the design of rectifier power supplies for vacuum tube equipment such as radio receivers or amplifiers.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] They are commonly found in direct-current motor controllers to produce direct current (DC), where they were used in conjunction with large electrolytic capacitors to remove the voltage ripple (AC) at the output DC.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] A rectifier circuit designed for a choke-output filter may produce too much DC output voltage and subject the rectifier and filter capacitors to excessive in-rush and ripple currents if the inductor is removed.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] However, modern electrolytic capacitors with high ripple current ratings, and voltage regulators that remove more power supply ripple than chokes could, have eliminated heavy, bulky chokes from mains frequency power supplies.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Smaller chokes are used in switching power supplies to remove the higher-frequency switching transients from the output and sometimes from feeding back into the mains input.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Some car audio hobbyists use choke coils with automobile audio systems (specifically in the wiring of a subwoofer, to remove high frequencies from the amplified signal).
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Radio frequency chokes (RFC) often have iron powder or ferrite cores which increases inductance and overall operation.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] They are often wound in complex patterns (basket winding) to reduce self-capacitance and proximity effect losses.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Chokes for even higher frequencies have non-magnetic cores and low inductance.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] A modern form of choke used for eliminating digital RF noise from lines is the ferrite bead, a cylindrical or torus-shaped core of ferrite slipped over a wire.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] These are often seen on computer cables.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] A common-mode (CM) choke is a special application where a choke is used to act upon a common-mode signal.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] These chokes are useful for suppression of electromagnetic interference (EMI) and radio frequency interference (RFI) frequently introduced on high current wires such as on power supply lines, which may cause unwanted operation.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Reducing this noise is frequently done by using a common mode choke—two parallel coil windings on a single core.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Common mode chokes allow differential currents to pass while blocking signals that are affecting both wires.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Because the magnetic flux produced by differential-mode currents in the core of a common mode choke tend to cancel each other out, the choke presents little impedance to differential mode currents.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] It achieves this by the placement of windings such that they generate equal but opposite fields that cancel each other out for differential mode signals.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] Normally this also means that the core will not saturate for large differential mode currents, and the maximum current rating is instead determined by the heating effect of the winding resistance.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] On the other hand, common mode currents see a high impedance path due to the combined inductance of the windings that reinforce each other.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] CM chokes are commonly used in industrial, electrical and telecommunications applications to remove or decrease noise and related electromagnetic interference.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] When the CM choke is conducting CM current, most of the magnetic flux generated by the windings is confined within the inductor core because of its high permeability.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] In this case, the leakage flux, which is also the near magnetic field emission of the CM choke is low.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] However, the DM current flowing through the windings will generate high emitted near magnetic field since the windings are negative coupled in this case.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] To reduce the near magnetic field emission, a twisted winding structure can be applied to the CM choke.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] The difference between the balanced twisted windings CM choke and conventional balanced two winding CM choke is that the windings interact in the center of the core open window.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] When it is conducting CM current, the balanced twisted winding CM inductor can provide identical CM inductance as the conventional CM inductor.
[src:braid-breaker/choke-electronics] When it is conducting DM current, the equivalent current loops will generate inversed direction magnetic fields in space so that they tend to cancel each other.
